243
00:23:23,145 --> 00:23:25,950
Yes, it's been this way all morning.

244
00:23:26,264 --> 00:23:28,475
May I help you out?

245
00:23:51,708 --> 00:23:55,077
It will only be a slight sting,
you needn't worry.

246
00:24:06,811 --> 00:24:08,182
I feel a little better.

247
00:24:08,296 --> 00:24:14,753
Oriental medicine is
based on the five elements theory.

248
00:24:15,443 --> 00:24:21,052
That is, wood, fire,
earth, metal and water.

249
00:24:22,024 --> 00:24:31,913
These five elements regulate
all the organs' activity in the human body.

250
00:24:32,538 --> 00:24:34,412
Fascinating.

251
00:24:34,911 --> 00:24:38,510
You're well versed
in Oriental medicine,

252
00:24:38,618 --> 00:24:42,677
and even studied western
medicine in your motherland.

253
00:24:42,800 --> 00:24:49,086
I think studying medicine here
in Germany would suit you perfectly.

254
00:24:49,865 --> 00:24:53,298
You will become a very
esteemed and talented doctor.

255
00:25:17,734 --> 00:25:20,339
Do you wash your hands
that way at home, too?

256
00:25:22,306 --> 00:25:23,023
Why?

257
00:25:23,118 --> 00:25:24,895
Your face and
body as well, I suppose.

258
00:25:24,989 --> 00:25:26,488
Yes. And?

259
00:25:26,689 --> 00:25:30,032
So why is your skin still so dirty?

260
00:25:47,140 --> 00:25:49,793
Hey, I brought someone
from your hometown.

261
00:25:51,010 --> 00:25:52,741
From my hometown?!

262
00:25:54,350 --> 00:25:57,334
Are you a compatriot of mine?

263
00:25:54,350 --> 00:25:57,334
{\a6}"C'est mon compatriote?"*

264
00:25:57,847 --> 00:26:00,578
Why don't you talk to him?

265
00:26:00,683 --> 00:26:03,958
Speak your mother tongue, that is.

266
00:26:05,506 --> 00:26:10,978
Sadly, people from my hometown
and I speak a different dialect,

267
00:26:11,149 --> 00:26:19,277
just like you can't easily understand
what professors from other regions say.

268
00:26:20,856 --> 00:26:22,584
Isn't it?

269
00:26:26,080 --> 00:26:28,310
<i>Elizabeth!
Don't run!</i>

270
00:26:30,092 --> 00:26:31,843
Are you all right?

271
00:26:33,710 --> 00:26:35,876
Nothing to be afraid of.

272
00:26:36,001 --> 00:26:40,638
Because I come from another land,
the color of my skin is different.

273
00:26:41,118 --> 00:26:42,789
Do you understand?

274
00:26:44,147 --> 00:26:45,297
Thank you.

275
00:26:45,582 --> 00:26:49,875
Do all men from your hometown
have the same skin?

276
00:26:50,164 --> 00:26:51,322
Yes.

277
00:26:52,163 --> 00:26:55,282
Is it because they
don't drink enough milk?

278
00:26:57,185 --> 00:27:03,116
This land I come from
is a little country from the far east.

279
00:27:03,255 --> 00:27:08,201
The people living there all
have dark hair and yellow skin.

280
00:27:08,297 --> 00:27:10,588
Ahhh... it must be the sun
that makes your skin yellow.

281
00:27:10,695 --> 00:27:14,939
It takes a such a long time to
reach us it doesn't have enough power,

282
00:27:15,439 --> 00:27:20,431
so we're all white.

283
00:27:22,458 --> 00:27:24,784
Yes, probably.

284
00:27:24,894 --> 00:27:26,627
I'm Elizabeth.

285
00:27:26,878 --> 00:27:28,903
And my name is Mirok.

286
00:27:28,997 --> 00:27:30,464
Mirok?!

287
00:27:30,712 --> 00:27:37,838
Mirok means being
foolish but of good heart!

288
00:27:40,070 --> 00:27:42,820
When I was
this little just like you,

289
00:27:43,103 --> 00:27:47,355
I must have looked like a fool,
but at least I looked kind,

290
00:27:47,531 --> 00:27:52,285
so that's probably
why they called me that.

291
00:27:52,549 --> 00:27:53,611
Uh?

292
00:27:54,535 --> 00:27:56,185
Fool!

293
00:28:01,135 --> 00:28:03,318
You can't pay the rent again?

294
00:28:03,423 --> 00:28:05,358
I apologize,

295
00:28:05,468 --> 00:28:07,760
I will pay as soon as I can.

296
00:28:07,874 --> 00:28:11,597
You haven't paid for two months,
this can't go on anymore.

297
00:28:11,724 --> 00:28:14,005
<i>I'll only wait until
the end of this month,</i>

298
00:28:14,095 --> 00:28:16,029
otherwise you're out!

299
00:28:23,177 --> 00:28:25,379
<i>Mother.</i>

300
00:28:25,534 --> 00:28:28,528
<i>Have you been well?</i>

301
00:28:28,641 --> 00:28:33,448
<i>I'm wondering if the rest of
the family is healthy as well.</i>

302
00:28:33,770 --> 00:28:36,720
<i>I'm doing fine.</i>

303
00:28:36,958 --> 00:28:39,909
<i>We'll start practicing at the
hospital, beginning this month.</i>

304
00:28:40,015 --> 00:28:43,722
<i>They're all very kind to me,</i>

305
00:28:43,847 --> 00:28:48,563
<i>and the owner of this
boarding house dotes on me like a mother.</i>

306
00:28:53,310 --> 00:28:55,711
Throw everything out!

307
00:28:55,837 --> 00:28:59,752
From now on, this place will
be used by the Imperial Police.

308
00:29:00,658 --> 00:29:04,621
Erase any trace of the
traitors' shadows as well.

309
00:29:08,418 --> 00:29:11,298
<i>I'm glad you're doing well.</i>

310
00:29:11,424 --> 00:29:14,903
<i>We're doing fine.</i>

311
00:29:15,054 --> 00:29:21,372
<i>Our only concern is you,
living alone in such a far away land.</i>

312
00:29:22,190 --> 00:29:24,891
<i>We recently moved.</i>

313
00:29:25,016 --> 00:29:28,323
<i>Our house started
languishing in its old age,</i>

314
00:29:28,444 --> 00:29:32,121
<i>so everything feels
fresh in this new house.</i>

315
00:29:32,250 --> 00:29:35,303
<i>It's full of rooms and
with a very large yard,</i>

316
00:29:35,437 --> 00:29:38,017
<i>it makes you feel elated.</i>

317
00:29:38,408 --> 00:29:41,578
<i>So, you needn't worry about us,</i>

318
00:29:41,730 --> 00:29:45,100
<i>and I wish you good health
and luck in your studies.</i>

319
00:29:56,162 --> 00:29:59,110
This is not worth much,

320
00:29:59,235 --> 00:30:03,443
but that watch over
there would certainly be better.

321
00:30:03,444 --> 00:30:05,724
<i>Care to give me that?</i>

322
00:30:10,223 --> 00:30:15,225
<i>Looks like it's the same
for Oriental philosophers,</i>

323
00:30:14,284 --> 00:30:20,976
worrying about the
time even for promenades.

324
00:30:26,771 --> 00:30:30,306
That's what Immanuel Kant did,
every single day.

325
00:30:30,433 --> 00:30:34,112
He took a walk at the
same exact time every day,

326
00:30:35,910 --> 00:30:38,708
so people said he was
trying to match his clock.

327
00:30:41,060 --> 00:30:43,536
Can I introduce myself?

328
00:30:44,148 --> 00:30:45,783
My name is Rosa.

329
00:30:46,331 --> 00:30:48,184
Mirok.

330
00:30:49,673 --> 00:30:51,085
Mirok Li.

331
00:30:51,211 --> 00:30:54,145
What does your name mean?

332
00:30:54,726 --> 00:31:02,462
{\A6}[*Mireuk = Maitreya]

333
00:30:54,726 --> 00:31:02,462
Mirok* in Buddhism is a future Buddha
who's come to save all men,

334
00:31:02,839 --> 00:31:07,392
creating a peaceful world to live in.

335
00:31:09,327 --> 00:31:14,018
That's the kind of peaceful
world you'll make, one day.

336
00:31:19,729 --> 00:31:23,183
You think I'm going to die?

337
00:31:23,217 --> 00:31:24,785
Elizabeth!

338
00:31:24,818 --> 00:31:30,272
That's what the doctor
told me, Aunt Rosa.

339
00:31:30,400 --> 00:31:31,244
No.

340
00:31:31,365 --> 00:31:33,459
That's not what I think.

341
00:31:34,818 --> 00:31:40,258
Whatever happens to me,
will you stay by my side?

342
00:31:40,355 --> 00:31:43,117
Of course I will.

343
00:31:44,562 --> 00:31:46,096
I'm not going anywhere.

344
00:31:46,203 --> 00:31:49,213
But you probably
will not be able to.

345
00:31:50,617 --> 00:31:52,178
Why wouldn't I?

346
00:31:52,301 --> 00:31:56,248
Because she likes
you more than I do.

347
00:31:59,507 --> 00:32:01,742
Elizabeth.

348
00:32:01,878 --> 00:32:05,269
I really care about you.

349
00:32:47,453 --> 00:32:49,637
Stop!

350
00:33:04,177 --> 00:33:09,649
A friend of mine was shot
to death by Japanese troops.

351
00:33:11,069 --> 00:33:17,281
Another was arrested.
Before they could get me, I ran away,

352
00:33:17,624 --> 00:33:20,089
and came all the
way here to Germany.

353
00:33:21,835 --> 00:33:28,680
Without even realizing it,
everything came back to mind.

354
00:33:36,605 --> 00:33:41,882
No one will harm you
here, it's a safe place.

355
00:34:19,826 --> 00:34:21,097
<i>Mother!</i>

356
00:34:21,833 --> 00:34:23,143
Mother!

357
00:34:23,831 --> 00:34:25,890
Mother!
Are you all right?

358
00:34:25,995 --> 00:34:27,326
Mother!

359
00:34:53,637 --> 00:34:54,813
Please.

360
00:34:54,935 --> 00:34:56,217
You must save her.

361
00:34:56,340 --> 00:34:57,852
The patient is already dead.

362
00:34:57,968 --> 00:35:00,583
But her hands are still warm!

363
00:35:00,692 --> 00:35:02,082
The machines don't lie.

364
00:35:02,191 --> 00:35:05,465
She's still alive,
her hands are warm!

365
00:35:05,574 --> 00:35:09,113
You're not suited to be a doctor.

366
00:35:09,226 --> 00:35:12,015
People who can't be
objective with their patients...

367
00:35:12,141 --> 00:35:14,637
are not qualified for this job.

368
00:36:07,879 --> 00:36:09,454
Mother!

369
00:36:10,711 --> 00:36:12,481
<i>Mother!</i>

370
00:36:12,623 --> 00:36:15,775
- Mother!
- <I>Mister Li!

371
00:36:31,794 --> 00:36:34,735
You're all burning.

372
00:36:35,493 --> 00:36:38,595
I received a letter from home.

373
00:36:40,935 --> 00:36:43,512
My mother passed away.

374
00:37:56,268 --> 00:38:00,515
So you're leaving the hospital?

375
00:38:03,387 --> 00:38:08,545
<i>The human body is like
a small universe in itself,</i>

376
00:38:08,560 --> 00:38:10,716
<i>a vessel embodying a man's soul,</i>

377
00:38:11,674 --> 00:38:15,784
<i>but nobody seems
interested about that here.</i>

378
00:38:18,456 --> 00:38:22,309
I think the path I'm walking
could lead me elsewhere.

379
00:38:23,167 --> 00:38:27,411
Spiritual enlightenment is
much more important to me.

380
00:38:28,950 --> 00:38:33,958
That's a relief.

381
00:38:34,648 --> 00:38:39,184
{\a6}[*Munchen = Munich]

382
00:38:34,648 --> 00:38:39,184
I'm leaving for Munchen*,
to study literature.

383
00:38:39,795 --> 00:38:41,972
See those gates?

384
00:38:42,096 --> 00:38:52,301
{\a6}[*Frederick V = King of Bohemia and
Elector Palatine of the Holy Roman Empire, 1596~1632*]

385
00:38:42,096 --> 00:38:43,481
It was commissioned
by Friedrich the Fifth*,

386
00:38:44,867 --> 00:38:52,301
and built in a single night, to
make his consort Elizabeth happy.

387
00:38:54,607 --> 00:38:58,819
They say when lovers
pass through these gates,

388
00:39:00,201 --> 00:39:03,780
their love will
last a hundred years.

389
00:39:08,061 --> 00:39:11,851
Mirok, should we
pass through as well?

390
00:39:14,154 --> 00:39:16,698
Or maybe not.

391
00:39:16,823 --> 00:39:22,407
If we go through, we could
be a hundred years together.

392
00:39:23,333 --> 00:39:27,010
But if we don't...

393
00:39:27,370 --> 00:39:30,321
it could be forever.

394
00:39:36,734 --> 00:39:38,364
Mirok.

395
00:39:39,172 --> 00:39:42,981
Will you come to Munchen with me?

396
00:39:45,134 --> 00:39:49,905
There, you can find the inspiration
to live life as you wish,

397
00:39:50,415 --> 00:39:54,066
to walk your own path.

398
00:40:15,360 --> 00:40:17,000
Mi Reuk!

399
00:40:17,748 --> 00:40:18,752
Jae Won.

400
00:40:18,782 --> 00:40:21,449
The applications for
publication end this month,

401
00:40:21,547 --> 00:40:23,414
but I already
mentioned them your name.

402
00:40:24,117 --> 00:40:25,601
Thank you,
but I'll have to decline.

403
00:40:25,712 --> 00:40:28,878
- Look.
- It's just that I wouldn't make it.

404
00:40:29,938 --> 00:40:32,078
I was writing something,
but haven't finished yet.

405
00:40:32,187 --> 00:40:36,536
Ahh... really, aren't you about
to be kicked out of that place?

406
00:40:42,338 --> 00:40:44,351
What are you writing?

407
00:40:46,787 --> 00:40:50,361
I'm trying to write
my first short story.

408
00:40:53,023 --> 00:40:54,413
What is it about?

409
00:40:56,751 --> 00:40:59,246
It's about a messenger from heaven.

410
00:41:00,471 --> 00:41:02,381
Do you mean angels?

411
00:41:21,164 --> 00:41:24,534
<i>Two poets were walking
the streets of Seoul one night,</i>

412
00:41:24,644 --> 00:41:28,876
<i>when they suddenly heard a woman's
voice coming from over the fence.</i>

413
00:41:28,969 --> 00:41:36,592
{\a6}[*nyang = old Joseon monetary unit*]

414
00:41:28,969 --> 00:41:32,786
<i>She was praying to the
gods to give her 1 nyang* to free her son,</i>

415
00:41:32,800 --> 00:41:36,592
<i>who had been
incarcerated because of her.</i>

416
00:41:37,848 --> 00:41:41,278
{\a6}[*10 don = 1 nyang*]

417
00:41:37,848 --> 00:41:41,021
<i>The older poet only had 7 don,*</i>

418
00:41:41,000 --> 00:41:43,964
<i>so he threw what
he had over the fence.</i>

419
00:41:44,349 --> 00:41:47,258
<i>A few days later, the younger
poet passed there once again,</i>

420
00:41:47,362 --> 00:41:49,709
<i>and he heard that woman again.</i>

421
00:41:49,811 --> 00:41:55,000
<i>She was still praying to the gods,
asking for just another 3 don.</i>

422
00:41:57,845 --> 00:42:02,804
<i>The young poet threw the 1
nyang he had over the fence.</i>

423
00:42:02,931 --> 00:42:06,612
<i>He was waiting to get
the difference back,</i>

424
00:42:06,720 --> 00:42:10,389
<i>but all he heard was this woman,
still praying to the gods,</i>

425
00:42:10,685 --> 00:42:13,274
<i>saying she'd use the remaining
money to feed her son for a few days,</i>

426
00:42:13,381 --> 00:42:16,815
<i>after all that time starving.</i>

427
00:42:18,419 --> 00:42:22,445
<i>The young poet just
went home, smiling.</i>

428
00:42:24,269 --> 00:42:26,515
I love it.

429
00:42:30,174 --> 00:42:32,896
That messenger of heaven,

430
00:42:33,086 --> 00:42:36,046
I wish you had one by your side.

431
00:42:37,685 --> 00:42:41,336
Will other people like it?

432
00:42:42,707 --> 00:42:51,291
Will German people understand
and enjoy a story from the far east?

433
00:42:51,899 --> 00:42:57,308
I love you.

434
00:42:58,900 --> 00:43:00,835
See? I understood.

435
00:43:03,354 --> 00:43:09,015
Just express your feelings,
with honesty and simplicity.

436
00:43:11,324 --> 00:43:17,225
Then, other people will understand
and interpret your feelings.

437
00:43:17,335 --> 00:43:19,186
Thank you, Rosa.

438
00:43:19,966 --> 00:43:21,871
Of course.

439
00:43:21,996 --> 00:43:26,382
You can love me, if you want.

440
00:43:26,487 --> 00:43:29,690
Your Korean has
gotten a lot better?!

441
00:43:31,948 --> 00:43:34,400
If I want to understand
what beats inside there,

442
00:43:34,500 --> 00:43:36,339
I must do that.

443
00:44:01,522 --> 00:44:07,246
I thought there was no path
past this labyrinth of mountains and rivers.

444
00:44:07,365 --> 00:44:15,478
But I found a village of bright
flowers and the willows's shade.

445
00:44:18,317 --> 00:44:23,751
It's a poem about finding hope in
a village where flowers bloom,

446
00:44:25,578 --> 00:44:32,319
after enduring the despair
of losing one's path.

447
00:44:33,645 --> 00:44:35,672
<i>Hello.</i>

448
00:44:36,640 --> 00:44:38,870
My name is Seyler.

449
00:44:38,988 --> 00:44:43,988
{\a6}[*LMU = Ludwig-Maximilians-Universitat Munchen*]

450
00:44:38,988 --> 00:44:42,678
I teach Art at the LMU*
here in Munchen.

451
00:44:42,602 --> 00:44:47,343
I've heard you're an
expert in East-Asian culture.

452
00:45:01,044 --> 00:45:04,024
I am grateful
for your inviting me here.

453
00:45:06,499 --> 00:45:09,228
How long has it been since
you've left your homeland?

454
00:45:10,571 --> 00:45:12,058
Over ten years.

455
00:45:15,018 --> 00:45:18,494
You must be really missing
your friends and family.

456
00:45:18,628 --> 00:45:21,664
Don't you feel lonely?

457
00:45:34,742 --> 00:45:41,560
<i>{\a6}"Sa Hae Ji Nae"</i>

458
00:45:34,742 --> 00:45:41,560
<i>"May you wise man whelm
thine life with heaven's order,"</i>

459
00:45:46,102 --> 00:45:50,102
<i>{\a6}"Gaehyeong...(je)"</i>

460
00:45:46,102 --> 00:45:49,500
<i>"And all creation shall
be thine brethren."</i>

461
00:45:50,218 --> 00:45:51,701
Ohhh... that's a bone!

462
00:45:57,157 --> 00:46:04,245
I think I'll have to call these Chinese
characters "bone scriptures," from now on.

463
00:46:07,555 --> 00:46:11,930
"Sahaejinae
Gaehyeongje."

464
00:46:14,270 --> 00:46:19,746
A pupil of the Oriental
philosoper Confucius...

465
00:46:20,104 --> 00:46:28,389
worried that, while everyone
had brethren, he was alone.

466
00:46:29,136 --> 00:46:32,459
<i>Confucius then said that,</i>

467
00:46:35,175 --> 00:46:38,923
<i>if you behave with decorum
and politeness to everyone,</i>

468
00:46:39,463 --> 00:46:42,948
<i>all the world is your brethren.</i>

469
00:46:43,400 --> 00:46:49,095
So why are you losing yourself in anxiety,
saying you have no brethren?

470
00:46:50,352 --> 00:46:53,628
You and I,

471
00:46:53,737 --> 00:46:59,683
we are not of the same race,
and we don't speak the same language.

472
00:46:59,800 --> 00:47:05,547
<i>But I think what we all have in
common is that we're all people.</i>

473
00:47:06,907 --> 00:47:12,288
<i>Because with affection
and understanding,</i>

474
00:47:12,413 --> 00:47:18,921
then all men can be friends,
and become family.

475
00:47:19,028 --> 00:47:21,255
And I have faith in this...

476
00:47:25,524 --> 00:47:28,591
So I feel no loneliness at all.

477
00:47:36,171 --> 00:47:38,808
What are you going to do now?

478
00:47:39,839 --> 00:47:42,566
I'll find a way.

479
00:47:43,956 --> 00:47:47,248
Can you hand me those books?

480
00:47:47,357 --> 00:47:50,136
- Where?
- There, on my bed.

481
00:48:03,471 --> 00:48:05,033
What's wrong?

482
00:48:11,067 --> 00:48:12,740
Come in.

483
00:48:15,935 --> 00:48:18,025
Doctor Li.

484
00:48:18,337 --> 00:48:19,543
<i>Hello.</i>

485
00:48:20,272 --> 00:48:22,596
I must have
chosen the wrong time.

486
00:48:22,689 --> 00:48:23,648
Ahh... no, no!

487
00:48:23,751 --> 00:48:27,885
I've been forced
to move in a hurry.

488
00:48:27,993 --> 00:48:30,058
Where are you going?

489
00:48:54,966 --> 00:48:57,263
Welcome, Doctor Li.

490
00:48:57,368 --> 00:48:58,451
I'm really grateful.

491
00:48:58,573 --> 00:49:01,756
You can think of this as your house,

492
00:49:01,913 --> 00:49:06,107
and should you need anything,
you can ask Lina here.

493
00:49:06,874 --> 00:49:08,478
Hello.

494
00:49:22,023 --> 00:49:24,989
Sahaejinae Gaehyeongje

495
00:49:39,325 --> 00:49:42,042
This is wonderful.

496
00:49:42,292 --> 00:49:45,942
Now there's nothing
you should worry about,

497
00:49:46,156 --> 00:49:48,624
you can finally write in peace.

498
00:49:48,729 --> 00:49:52,616
It's all thanks to those people.

499
00:49:53,180 --> 00:49:57,066
I sent my final draft to the publisher.

500
00:50:00,399 --> 00:50:01,836
Rosa!

501
00:50:08,448 --> 00:50:11,100
I'm sorry, Mirok.

502
00:50:12,338 --> 00:50:14,938
It slipped from my fingers.

503
00:50:15,203 --> 00:50:16,342
Come in.

504
00:50:20,790 --> 00:50:23,787
It's a package for you,
from Korea.

505
00:50:25,173 --> 00:50:26,637
Thank you.

506
00:50:48,197 --> 00:50:50,508
It's so beautiful.

507
00:50:52,098 --> 00:50:54,771
These clothes,

508
00:50:55,686 --> 00:50:58,591
and your wife,
who made them for you.

509
00:51:01,363 --> 00:51:04,843
I'm just fine, Mirok.

510
00:51:05,731 --> 00:51:09,569
You haven't betrayed
your wife even once.

511
00:51:09,711 --> 00:51:12,398
And that's the reason I liked you.

512
00:51:17,651 --> 00:51:21,396
It's soft and beautiful.

513
00:51:21,894 --> 00:51:28,185
Do they make
these for women, too?

514
00:51:34,081 --> 00:51:37,114
<i>I am grateful for
the clothes you sent me.</i>

515
00:51:38,466 --> 00:51:41,588
<i>I need a favor from you.</i>

516
00:51:41,708 --> 00:51:46,095
<i>I'd like you to make me a skirt.</i>

517
00:52:09,694 --> 00:52:14,373
{\a6}[*Famous work by female
poet Heo Nanseolheon]

518
00:52:09,694 --> 00:52:14,373
<i>The blue sky and white
clouds sing my prose.*</i>

519
00:52:14,513 --> 00:52:19,489
<i>Altair and Vega bedeck
the deep, starry night.</i>

520
00:52:19,614 --> 00:52:23,794
<i>Where art thou,
O my beloved?</i>

521
00:52:23,912 --> 00:52:29,301
<i>The rain of tears my heart
sheds, as vast as the ocean.</i>

522
00:52:29,989 --> 00:52:32,753
<i>Just remember this.</i>

523
00:52:32,858 --> 00:52:35,402
That...

524
00:52:36,170 --> 00:52:39,036
I will always be here for you.

525
00:53:21,999 --> 00:53:26,382
[*Nights in a Korean alleyway."
Mirok Li*]

526
00:54:20,457 --> 00:54:23,842
I've been looking for you.

527
00:54:46,832 --> 00:54:51,374
My short story was published.

528
00:54:52,185 --> 00:54:54,182
I wanted you to be
the first I'd show it to.

529
00:54:54,291 --> 00:54:56,800
Congratulations.

530
00:54:57,255 --> 00:54:59,876
It's all thanks to you.

531
00:55:00,036 --> 00:55:06,463
You've always encouraged me,
and gave me strength.

532
00:55:14,396 --> 00:55:20,495
This is a small token
of my gratitude.

533
00:55:27,904 --> 00:55:30,495
Open it for me.

534
00:55:55,738 --> 00:55:59,073
It's really soft.

535
00:56:00,543 --> 00:56:02,352
Mirok.

536
00:56:03,540 --> 00:56:06,670
If that day...

537
00:56:06,972 --> 00:56:10,758
we passed through those gates,

538
00:56:11,758 --> 00:56:15,206
would our love have come true?

539
00:56:25,124 --> 00:56:27,345
Mirok.

540
00:56:30,477 --> 00:56:34,007
I can see you.

541
00:56:39,855 --> 00:56:43,457
Multiple sclerosis.

542
00:56:47,936 --> 00:56:50,338
I...

543
00:56:54,954 --> 00:56:56,893
I don't have
much longer to live.

544
00:56:56,985 --> 00:56:58,557
But... how did...

545
00:56:59,319 --> 00:57:03,722
When I leave this world,

546
00:57:08,949 --> 00:57:14,019
I will wear these
clothes you gave me.

547
00:57:43,830 --> 00:57:49,197
<i>I wish the path which led
you to leave your homeland...</i>

548
00:57:51,366 --> 00:57:56,183
<i>and find refuge here will be
always as happy and peaceful as it is now,</i>

549
00:57:56,298 --> 00:57:58,585
<i>Mirok</i>

